362","1390":"1390","1405":"1405","Dundonald Castle, Irvine, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Irvine, Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland","Rowallan, Kilmannock, Ayr, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1320–1355":"1320–1355","1316–1390":"1316–1390","1338–1362":"1338–1362","1340–1405":"1340–1405","1340–1420":"1340–1420","–Female":"Deceased","1338":"1338","1316":"1316","22 November 1347":"22 November 1347","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1362":"1362","1390":"1390","1405":"1405","Dundonald Castle, Irvine, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Irvine, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Rowallan, Kilmannock, Ayr, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mure","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): variant of   Morea  .","Scottish: variant of   Muir  .","English: occupational name from Old French <i>muer</i> ‘mewer’, i.e. someone who tended to hawks in the cages in which they were kept while moulting. Compare   Mew  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mura","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Akio, Hideo, Masao, Nanako, Tsutomu, Yoshi.  French Alphonse, Amie, Henri.","German: altered form of some similar (like-sounding) German or perhaps French surname. It is also common in France (Alsace), where it was first recorded in the form <i>Morrau</i>, later <i>Murra(w)</i>.","Italian (southern Sardinia): topographic name or nickname from Sardinian <i>mura</i> ‘mulberry’ or ‘blackberry’."]},{"name":"Muir","meanings":["Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived on a moor, from Older Scots <i>muir</i> ‘moor’ (an expanse of bare, wild upland country). There has been some confusion with   Mure  ."]},{"name":"Morea","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Saverio, Domenic, Ferdinando, Rocco.  Spanish Manuel, Carlos, Cesar, Elvira, Jesus, Mauricio.","Italian (Apulia): from the personal name <i>Morea</i>, originally a habitational name from Morea, the medieval name of the Greek region of Peloponnese, named as the land of mulberry trees, from <i>mōrea</i> ‘mulberry’.","Spanish and Catalan: habitational name from any of the places called Morea, in Badajoz, Navarre, and Lleida provinces."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Countess of Atholl Elizabeth Mure was born in 1320, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married Robert Earl of Strathearn Stewart on 22 November 1347. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 4 daughters. She died in 1355, in Scotland, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1320–1355":"1320–1355","1316–1390":"1316–1390","1338–1362":"1338–1362","1340–1405":"1340–1405","1340–1420":"1340–1420","–Female":"Surnud","1338":"1338","1316":"